Quiz02_01: 50 points
(FnA1szLongestMonoSubsequence)
Status: Solved with testing
Strategy:
  Standard quadratic-time dynamic programming, going right-to-left.
  Let L[i] be the length of the longest non-decreasing subsequence
  starting at index i, and let nxt[i] be the smallest index j > i
  with xs[j] >= xs[i] and L[j] = L[i] - 1 (i.e. the leftmost choice
  that still attains the maximum length).
  Computing L and nxt is O(n^2) because the inner loop scans every
  j > i. The answer is reconstructed by starting at the smallest
  index s with L[s] = max(L) and walking the nxt chain; choosing
  the leftmost start and the leftmost next at every step gives the
  lexicographically smallest sequence of indices among all longest
  non-decreasing subsequences, which matches the spec ("longest
  leftmost ascending"). Total time: O(n^2).

############################################################

Quiz02_02: 50 points
(sort1000WithNoRecursion)
Status: Solved with testing
Strategy:
  Plain iterative insertion sort with two nested loops and no
  recursion. For each i = 1..n-1 we shift larger predecessors one
  slot to the right and drop the saved key into the gap. On a
  "nearly sorted" sequence (every element at most a constant
  distance from its sorted position) the inner shift loop only
  does O(1) work per pass, so the entire sort runs in O(n) time;
  this scales comfortably to N = 10^6 (test runs in tens of ms).

############################################################

Quiz02_03: 50 points
(GameOf24_dfs_solve and GameOf24_bfs_solve)
Status: Solved with testing
Strategy:
  The state of an in-progress Game-of-24 game is the list of
  Terms still on the table. Initially this list contains the four
  TermInts. A "move" combines any two terms in the list with one
  of {+, -, *, /} into a single TermOpr that takes their place,
  shrinking the list by one. After three moves exactly one term
  remains; the game is solved iff that term evaluates to 24.

  I model the search space as an FnGtree<FnList<Term>>:
    - the value() of a node is the current list of terms;
    - the children() of a node is the list of all states reachable
      in exactly one move (every ordered pair of operands times
      every operator).
  GameOf24_dfs_solve calls FnGtreeSUtil.DFirstEnumerate(root) and
  GameOf24_bfs_solve calls FnGtreeSUtil.BFirstEnumerate(root).
  Both return the same set of finished games as a stream of
  FnList<Term>; I then keep only those of length 1 whose single
  term evaluates to 24 and map them to that term, producing the
  required LnStrm<Term>.

