Quiz02_04:
30 points plus up to 20 bonus points
(isAVL and genAVLBST)
Status: Solved with testing (single-pass implementation, eligible
for the bonus)

Strategy for isAVL:
  A single post-order traversal computes and returns the height of
  each subtree, and returns -1 to signal "not an AVL". Each node is
  visited exactly once, so the algorithm is linear time and only
  needs O(h) stack space, qualifying for the bonus.

Strategy for genAVLBST and the answer to "what is this height?":
  Let f(h) be the minimum number of nodes any AVL tree of height h
  can contain (Fibonacci-tree counts):
    f(0)=0, f(1)=1, f(h) = 1 + f(h-1) + f(h-2).
  Any AVL of height h must have at least f(h) nodes. Therefore the
  maximum height that an AVL on N nodes can possibly have is the
  largest h with f(h) <= N. With N = 1_000_000 we have
    f(28) = 832039 <= 1_000_000 < 1_346_268 = f(29),
  so the maximum achievable height is **h = 28**.

  genAVLBST builds, by recursion, an AVL of height exactly 28 with
  exactly 1_000_000 nodes: at every internal node it picks heights
  for the two children (differing by at most 1 and with the maximum
  equal to h-1) and a corresponding split of the remaining (n-1)
  nodes into the two subtrees, taking advantage of the fact that an
  AVL of height h can hold any number between f(h) and 2^h - 1
  nodes. Keys are assigned in an in-order walk so the resulting
  tree is also a BST whose keys are 0,1,...,999999. The test code
  verifies isAVL, BST property, the size (1_000_000), and that the
  height is 28.

  Why this gives the maximal height: f(h) is, by definition, the
  *minimum* number of nodes needed to reach height h, so the largest
  h with f(h) <= N is the height of the *thinnest* (i.e. tallest
  for given N) legal AVL. Any taller tree would need at least
  f(h+1) > N nodes, which we do not have.

