Quiz02_06: 50 points
(reroot and insert on DBST)
Status: Solved with testing
Strategy:
  The BST stores int keys; every node holds a parent pointer,
  left/right children, and the size of its subtree.

  reroot():
    1. choose a random node by drawing a uniformly random index in
       [0, root.size - 1] and finding the corresponding in-order
       node via the size fields (O(h)).
    2. rotate the chosen node toward the root using right/left tree
       rotations: if the chosen node is a left child, do a right
       rotation at its parent; if it is a right child, do a left
       rotation. Each rotation preserves the BST property and only
       updates a constant number of parent / child / size fields
       around the rotation site.
    3. when the chosen node has no parent it has become the new
       root; update [root].

  insert(key):
    standard iterative BST insertion. Walk down following the BST
    property; if the key is already present, return false; otherwise
    link a fresh leaf into the parent's correct slot, set its parent
    pointer and size = 1, and bump the size field of every ancestor
    on the path to the root.

  The test code verifies (after both inserts and several reroots)
  the BST property, that parent pointers are consistent, and that
  every node's stored size is equal to one plus the sizes of its
  two children.

